 man, beginning with original goodness held captive by a servile will and ending with the possibility of liberation and regeneration of the heart, underpins his passion for the more than possible. The essays in this volume trace the fluid movement between phenomenological and religious descriptions of the capable self that emerges across Ricoeur's oeuvre and establish points of connection for future developments that might draw inspiration from this body of thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aBarash, Jeffrey Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlundell, Boyd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiasse, Gaëlle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreisch, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerda, Ellen A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKearney, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPellauer, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRasmussen, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRicoeur, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTreanor, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTreanor, Brian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVenema, Henry Isaac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVenema, Henry Isaac, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhtt